/* CISM :: content/quiz4.js — CISM Domain 4 question bank (100 items). */
window.CISM = window.CISM || {}; CISM.questions = CISM.questions || [];
CISM.questions.push.apply(CISM.questions, [
{"id":"D4-001","domain":4,"obj":"4A1","diff":"easy","q":"Which document establishes the authority, roles, and procedures an organization follows when responding to a security incident?","options":["Business impact analysis","Risk register","Incident response plan","Security awareness policy"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Incident response plan</strong> — the IRP is the authoritative document that defines roles, authority, activation criteria, and procedures for responding to incidents.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Business impact analysis</b>: identifies criticality and recovery requirements of processes, feeding the plan but not itself the response procedure document.</span><span class='qd'><b>Risk register</b>: tracks identified risks and treatment status, not incident response authority or procedures.</span><span class='qd'><b>Security awareness policy</b>: governs training content and cadence, unrelated to incident response authority.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-002","domain":4,"obj":"4A2","diff":"easy","q":"According to NIST SP 800-61, which phase of the incident response lifecycle occurs immediately after Detection & Analysis?","options":["Preparation","Containment, Eradication & Recovery","Post-Incident Activity","Notification"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Containment, Eradication & Recovery</strong> — once an incident is detected and analyzed, the next lifecycle phase limits damage, removes the cause, and restores operations.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Preparation</b>: is the first phase, occurring before detection, not after analysis.</span><span class='qd'><b>Post-Incident Activity</b>: is the final phase, occurring after containment/eradication/recovery is complete.</span><span class='qd'><b>Notification</b>: is not a named NIST 800-61 phase; it is an activity embedded within multiple phases.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-003","domain":4,"obj":"4A1","diff":"med","q":"An information security manager is building the organization's first computer security incident response team (CSIRT). Which factor MOST influences whether the team should be centralized or distributed?","options":["The preference of the chief information officer","The vendor selected for SIEM tooling","The color-coding scheme used for severity levels","The organization's geographic and business unit structure"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The organization's geographic and business unit structure</strong> — CSIRT topology should mirror how the business operates so escalation paths and local expertise align with where incidents occur.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The preference of the chief information officer</b>: input matters but is not the primary driver; structural fit with the business matters more.</span><span class='qd'><b>The vendor selected for SIEM tooling</b>: tooling supports the CSIRT but does not dictate its organizational model.</span><span class='qd'><b>The color-coding scheme used for severity levels</b>: is a classification convenience, not a structural driver.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-004","domain":4,"obj":"4A3","diff":"med","q":"A help desk technician receives a report of a user unable to access a file share. Upon investigation, the share was deleted by a misconfigured script. How should this be classified?","options":["An incident, since availability was impacted, but not a security breach","A confirmed data breach","A disaster requiring DR plan activation","A non-event, since no attacker was involved"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>An incident, since availability was impacted, but not a security breach</strong> — availability loss from a misconfiguration is a legitimate information security incident even without malicious intent or attacker involvement.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A confirmed data breach</b>: implies unauthorized disclosure of data, which did not occur here.</span><span class='qd'><b>A disaster requiring DR plan activation</b>: overstates scale; a single misconfigured share does not typically warrant full disaster declaration.</span><span class='qd'><b>A non-event, since no attacker was involved</b>: incorrectly assumes incidents require malicious intent; unintentional impacts to availability still qualify.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-005","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"easy","q":"Which analysis identifies the maximum tolerable downtime for critical business processes?","options":["Vulnerability assessment","Penetration test","Business impact analysis","Control self-assessment"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Business impact analysis</strong> — the BIA quantifies the operational and financial impact of downtime over time, establishing maximum tolerable downtime and recovery targets.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Vulnerability assessment</b>: identifies technical weaknesses, not business impact of downtime.</span><span class='qd'><b>Penetration test</b>: validates exploitability of vulnerabilities, unrelated to downtime tolerance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Control self-assessment</b>: evaluates control effectiveness through self-reporting, not downtime impact.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-006","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"easy","q":"The recovery point objective (RPO) for a system is defined as the:","options":["Maximum time allowed to restore a system after failure","Maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time","Minimum staffing level required during recovery","Cost of restoring the system to full operation"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time</strong> — RPO defines how much data, expressed as a time interval since the last good backup or replication point, the organization can tolerate losing.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Maximum time allowed to restore a system after failure</b>: describes recovery time objective (RTO), not RPO.</span><span class='qd'><b>Minimum staffing level required during recovery</b>: is a staffing/resourcing consideration, not RPO.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cost of restoring the system to full operation</b>: is a budgeting concern, not a time-based data loss metric.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-007","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"med","q":"A critical order-processing system replicates data every 4 hours. A failure occurs 3 hours after the last replication. Approximately how much data loss will the business experience relative to its RPO of 4 hours?","options":["Double the acceptable RPO threshold","A full day of data loss","Data loss cannot be estimated without RTO","Within the acceptable RPO threshold"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Within the acceptable RPO threshold</strong> — since the failure occurred 3 hours after replication, the actual data loss (3 hours) is less than the defined 4-hour RPO, so it remains within tolerance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Double the acceptable RPO threshold</b>: incorrectly doubles the interval; 3 hours is less than, not more than, the 4-hour RPO.</span><span class='qd'><b>A full day of data loss</b>: is unsupported by the scenario, which specifies a 4-hour replication cycle.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data loss cannot be estimated without RTO</b>: is incorrect; RPO alone determines data-loss exposure, independent of RTO.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-008","domain":4,"obj":"4B3","diff":"easy","q":"Which document describes the procedures for restoring IT systems and infrastructure after a disruptive event?","options":["Disaster recovery plan","Business continuity plan","Incident response plan","Communications plan"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Disaster recovery plan</strong> — the DRP focuses specifically on the technical restoration of IT systems, applications, and infrastructure following a disruption.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Business continuity plan</b>: addresses continuity of overall business operations and processes, broader than IT restoration alone.</span><span class='qd'><b>Incident response plan</b>: governs detection and handling of security incidents, not infrastructure restoration procedures.</span><span class='qd'><b>Communications plan</b>: governs messaging to stakeholders, not technical recovery steps.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-009","domain":4,"obj":"4B3","diff":"med","q":"Which is the correct hierarchical relationship among these planning documents?","options":["DRP is the umbrella plan; BCP is a subordinate technical component","IRP and BCP are identical in scope and purpose","BCP is the umbrella plan; DRP is a subordinate technical recovery component","DRP supersedes BCP once declared"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>BCP is the umbrella plan; DRP is a subordinate technical recovery component</strong> — the business continuity plan addresses continuation of critical business functions overall, while the disaster recovery plan is a supporting, IT-focused subset addressing technical restoration.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>DRP is the umbrella plan; BCP is a subordinate technical component</b>: reverses the correct hierarchy.</span><span class='qd'><b>IRP and BCP are identical in scope and purpose</b>: incorrectly conflates two distinct plans with different triggers and objectives.</span><span class='qd'><b>DRP supersedes BCP once declared</b>: is not a recognized governance relationship between these plans.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-010","domain":4,"obj":"4B4","diff":"easy","q":"Which type of recovery site has fully configured hardware, software, and near-real-time data replication, allowing the fastest failover?","options":["Warm site","Hot site","Cold site","Mobile site"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Hot site</strong> — a hot site is fully equipped and kept synchronized with production data, enabling near-immediate failover with minimal RTO.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Warm site</b>: has hardware and connectivity partially configured but requires additional setup and data restoration, producing a longer RTO.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cold site</b>: provides only basic facilities (power, space, cooling) with no pre-installed systems, requiring the longest RTO.</span><span class='qd'><b>Mobile site</b>: a transportable facility, typically used as a temporary or emergency option, not defined by real-time replication.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-011","domain":4,"obj":"4B4","diff":"med","q":"An organization has a very low tolerance for downtime but a limited recovery budget. Which recovery site strategy BEST balances these competing constraints?","options":["Hot site with full real-time mirroring at all locations","Cold site only","No secondary site; rely solely on backups","Warm site"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Warm site</strong> — a warm site offers a reasonable compromise, providing partially configured infrastructure that can be activated faster than a cold site at lower ongoing cost than a fully mirrored hot site.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Hot site with full real-time mirroring at all locations</b>: minimizes downtime but conflicts with the stated budget limitation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cold site only</b>: is the lowest cost but produces unacceptably long recovery times for low downtime tolerance.</span><span class='qd'><b>No secondary site; rely solely on backups</b>: leaves no facility for restoring operations, risking extended outages.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-012","domain":4,"obj":"4A4","diff":"med","q":"During a suspected ransomware outbreak, the incident manager wants to stop lateral spread without powering off the affected servers, since volatile memory may hold forensic evidence. Which action BEST achieves this?","options":["Isolate affected hosts from the network while leaving them powered on","Immediately shut down all affected hosts","Restore from backup before analysis","Disable the SIEM to reduce alert noise"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Isolate affected hosts from the network while leaving them powered on</strong> — network isolation (e.g., VLAN quarantine or disabling the NIC) stops propagation while preserving volatile memory for forensic capture.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Immediately shut down all affected hosts</b>: destroys volatile memory contents, eliminating evidence needed for root-cause analysis.</span><span class='qd'><b>Restore from backup before analysis</b>: risks reintroducing the threat and destroys the opportunity to determine scope and root cause.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disable the SIEM to reduce alert noise</b>: removes visibility precisely when monitoring is most needed.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-013","domain":4,"obj":"4A4","diff":"hard","q":"An incident responder must contain an active intrusion on a production database server that cannot be taken offline without violating a contractual SLA. Which containment strategy BEST reflects short-term containment while preserving business operations?","options":["Take the server fully offline despite the SLA","Wait until eradication is complete before taking any containment action","Apply targeted network segmentation and access restrictions around the host while continuing investigation","Rebuild the server immediately from a clean image"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Apply targeted network segmentation and access restrictions around the host while continuing investigation</strong> — short-term containment limits attacker capability without full shutdown, honoring the SLA while investigation proceeds.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Take the server fully offline despite the SLA</b>: ignores the business constraint the scenario explicitly requires the manager to respect.</span><span class='qd'><b>Wait until eradication is complete before taking any containment action</b>: reverses the correct sequence; containment precedes eradication.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rebuild the server immediately from a clean image</b>: is a recovery/eradication action taken too early, and destroys evidence before analysis.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-014","domain":4,"obj":"4A5","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following is an example of long-term containment, as opposed to short-term containment?","options":["Unplugging the network cable from an infected workstation","Applying temporary firewall rules while a permanent patched, rebuilt system is prepared","Powering off a compromised server immediately","Disabling a single compromised user account for a few minutes"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Applying temporary firewall rules while a permanent patched, rebuilt system is prepared</strong> — long-term containment involves sustained measures that keep systems operational and controlled while a durable fix is engineered, bridging to eradication.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Unplugging the network cable from an infected workstation</b>: is an immediate, short-term containment action, not a sustained strategy.</span><span class='qd'><b>Powering off a compromised server immediately</b>: is a rapid short-term action, not a long-term containment measure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling a single compromised user account for a few minutes</b>: is a brief, short-term measure rather than a sustained containment approach.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-015","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"easy","q":"Which forensic principle dictates that data should be collected starting with the most volatile evidence, such as CPU registers and RAM, before less volatile sources like disk?","options":["Chain of custody","Least privilege","Separation of duties","Order of volatility"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Order of volatility</strong> — this principle guides evidence collection sequencing so that the most perishable data is captured first, before it is lost.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Chain of custody</b>: tracks who handled evidence and when, not the sequence of collection by volatility.</span><span class='qd'><b>Least privilege</b>: an access control principle limiting permissions, unrelated to evidence collection order.</span><span class='qd'><b>Separation of duties</b>: an access control principle preventing single-person control over sensitive functions, unrelated to forensic sequencing.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-016","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"med","q":"A forensic investigator seizes a laptop as evidence. Which record MUST be maintained to ensure the evidence remains admissible in legal proceedings?","options":["Chain of custody log","Business impact analysis","Vulnerability scan report","Change management ticket"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Chain of custody log</strong> — a documented, unbroken chain of custody records every person who handled the evidence and when, which is essential to prove the evidence was not altered or tampered with.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Business impact analysis</b>: assesses process criticality, unrelated to evidentiary integrity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Vulnerability scan report</b>: documents technical weaknesses, not evidence handling.</span><span class='qd'><b>Change management ticket</b>: tracks authorized changes to systems, not forensic evidence custody.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-017","domain":4,"obj":"4A7","diff":"med","q":"Under the GDPR, a data controller that experiences a personal data breach likely to result in risk to individuals must notify the supervisory authority within which timeframe?","options":["24 hours of becoming aware of the breach","30 days of becoming aware of the breach","72 hours of becoming aware of the breach","Immediately, with no defined timeframe"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>72 hours of becoming aware of the breach</strong> — GDPR Article 33 requires notification to the supervisory authority without undue delay and, where feasible, within 72 hours of becoming aware.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>24 hours of becoming aware of the breach</b>: is shorter than the GDPR-mandated window.</span><span class='qd'><b>30 days of becoming aware of the breach</b>: is far longer than the GDPR requirement.</span><span class='qd'><b>Immediately, with no defined timeframe</b>: incorrectly implies GDPR sets no specific deadline.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-018","domain":4,"obj":"4A7","diff":"hard","q":"A multinational organization suffers a breach affecting EU residents' personal data. Legal counsel is still determining the full scope, and the 72-hour GDPR window is about to lapse. What is the MOST appropriate action?","options":["Delay notification until the investigation is fully complete","Submit an initial notification with known facts and indicate that further details will follow","Notify only the affected individuals and skip the supervisory authority","Wait for law enforcement to authorize disclosure before notifying anyone"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Submit an initial notification with known facts and indicate that further details will follow</strong> — GDPR explicitly permits phased notification, allowing organizations to report what is known within 72 hours and supplement details as the investigation progresses.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Delay notification until the investigation is fully complete</b>: violates the 72-hour requirement and risks regulatory penalty.</span><span class='qd'><b>Notify only the affected individuals and skip the supervisory authority</b>: fails to meet the separate, mandatory regulator notification obligation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Wait for law enforcement to authorize disclosure before notifying anyone</b>: is not a general GDPR exemption and would likely breach the deadline.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-019","domain":4,"obj":"4A8","diff":"easy","q":"Which technology aggregates and correlates log data from multiple sources to support real-time detection of security events?","options":["Business impact analysis tool","Configuration management database","Data loss prevention agent","Security information and event management (SIEM)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Security information and event management (SIEM)</strong> — a SIEM centralizes log collection, correlation, and alerting across the environment to support detection.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Business impact analysis tool</b>: supports BIA modeling, not real-time log correlation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Configuration management database</b>: tracks IT asset configurations, not security event correlation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data loss prevention agent</b>: monitors and blocks specific data exfiltration patterns, a narrower function than SIEM-wide correlation.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-020","domain":4,"obj":"4A8","diff":"med","q":"An organization wants to automate routine containment actions, such as isolating a host, once a SIEM alert reaches high confidence. Which technology BEST supports this automation?","options":["Security orchestration, automation, and response (SOAR)","Intrusion detection system alone","Antivirus signature database","Vulnerability scanner"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Security orchestration, automation, and response (SOAR)</strong> — SOAR platforms execute predefined playbooks that automatically trigger containment and response actions based on alert criteria.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Intrusion detection system alone</b>: detects and alerts but does not orchestrate automated response actions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Antivirus signature database</b>: identifies known malware signatures, not orchestration of response workflows.</span><span class='qd'><b>Vulnerability scanner</b>: identifies weaknesses proactively, unrelated to real-time automated response.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-021","domain":4,"obj":"4A9","diff":"easy","q":"Which activity occurs during the post-incident review phase of the incident response lifecycle?","options":["Isolating the compromised host from the network","Declaring the incident and activating the CSIRT","Conducting a lessons-learned meeting to identify process improvements","Applying a patch to eradicate the root cause"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Conducting a lessons-learned meeting to identify process improvements</strong> — post-incident review captures what worked, what failed, and what should change, feeding continuous improvement of the IRP.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Isolating the compromised host from the network</b>: is a containment activity, occurring earlier in the lifecycle.</span><span class='qd'><b>Declaring the incident and activating the CSIRT</b>: occurs during detection and analysis, not post-incident review.</span><span class='qd'><b>Applying a patch to eradicate the root cause</b>: is an eradication activity, preceding post-incident review.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-022","domain":4,"obj":"4B5","diff":"easy","q":"Which type of business continuity test involves participants discussing their roles and responses to a simulated scenario without activating actual systems?","options":["Full interruption test","Tabletop exercise","Parallel test","Simulation test with live failover"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Tabletop exercise</strong> — a tabletop is a discussion-based walkthrough where participants talk through their responses to a scenario, without invoking live systems.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Full interruption test</b>: actually shuts down primary operations and shifts to the recovery site, a high-risk, high-fidelity test.</span><span class='qd'><b>Parallel test</b>: runs the recovery site alongside production to validate functionality without interrupting live operations.</span><span class='qd'><b>Simulation test with live failover</b>: involves activating systems, unlike a purely discussion-based tabletop.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-023","domain":4,"obj":"4B5","diff":"med","q":"Which type of DR test provides the highest assurance of recovery capability but carries the greatest risk to production operations?","options":["Tabletop exercise","Checklist review","Structured walkthrough","Full interruption test"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Full interruption test</strong> — this test actually shifts operations to the recovery site, providing the most realistic validation but exposing the business to operational risk if the failover does not succeed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Tabletop exercise</b>: is low-risk and discussion-based, providing lower assurance than an actual failover.</span><span class='qd'><b>Checklist review</b>: verifies plan completeness on paper, with minimal risk and minimal assurance of operational capability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Structured walkthrough</b>: is a more detailed discussion exercise, still without live system activation.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-024","domain":4,"obj":"4A2","diff":"easy","q":"Which term describes any observable occurrence in a system or network, which may or may not indicate a security problem?","options":["Event","Incident","Breach","Disaster"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Event</strong> — an event is any observable occurrence; it becomes an incident only when it violates security policy or threatens confidentiality, integrity, or availability.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Incident</b>: is a subset of events that actually represents a security violation or threat, not every observable occurrence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Breach</b>: specifically implies unauthorized access to or disclosure of protected data, a narrower and more severe classification.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disaster</b>: denotes a large-scale disruptive event triggering business continuity or disaster recovery activation, far broader than a routine event.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-025","domain":4,"obj":"4A2","diff":"med","q":"An analyst notices unusual outbound traffic to an unfamiliar IP address at 2 a.m. Investigation confirms unauthorized data exfiltration. At what point did this scenario formally become an 'incident' rather than an 'event'?","options":["The moment the outbound traffic was logged by the firewall","When the SIEM generated any alert","When investigation confirmed the traffic represented unauthorized exfiltration","When the on-call analyst began their shift"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>When investigation confirmed the traffic represented unauthorized exfiltration</strong> — an occurrence becomes an incident once analysis confirms it violates policy or represents an actual security compromise, not merely because it was observed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The moment the outbound traffic was logged by the firewall</b>: logging alone is just an event record, not confirmation of compromise.</span><span class='qd'><b>When the SIEM generated any alert</b>: an alert only flags something for review; many alerts turn out to be false positives.</span><span class='qd'><b>When the on-call analyst began their shift</b>: is unrelated to the technical determination of incident status.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-026","domain":4,"obj":"4A3","diff":"med","q":"An organization's incident classification scheme assigns severity based primarily on which factor?","options":["The technical complexity of the attack technique used","Business impact and scope of the affected systems or data","The number of log entries generated","The time of day the incident was detected"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Business impact and scope of the affected systems or data</strong> — severity classification should prioritize incidents based on their actual or potential impact to the business, guiding resource allocation and escalation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The technical complexity of the attack technique used</b>: complexity does not necessarily correlate with business impact.</span><span class='qd'><b>The number of log entries generated</b>: is a volume metric unrelated to actual impact severity.</span><span class='qd'><b>The time of day the incident was detected</b>: may affect response logistics but is not a basis for severity classification.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-027","domain":4,"obj":"4A1","diff":"hard","q":"A CISO is drafting the charter for a newly formed CSIRT. Which statement BEST reflects a well-designed charter?","options":["It lists every employee's home phone number for emergency contact","It replaces the need for an incident response plan","It focuses exclusively on public relations messaging","It defines the team's mission, authority to act during incidents, and scope of systems covered"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>It defines the team's mission, authority to act during incidents, and scope of systems covered</strong> — an effective charter establishes the CSIRT's mandate, decision-making authority, and boundaries of responsibility so the team can act decisively during incidents.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It lists every employee's home phone number for emergency contact</b>: is an operational contact list detail, not the substance of a charter.</span><span class='qd'><b>It replaces the need for an incident response plan</b>: incorrectly conflates the charter, which defines the team, with the plan, which defines procedures.</span><span class='qd'><b>It focuses exclusively on public relations messaging</b>: is far too narrow; PR is only one component of overall incident communications.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-028","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"med","q":"During a BIA, which two metrics are typically derived for each critical business process?","options":["Recovery time objective and recovery point objective","Mean time between failures and mean time to repair","Annualized loss expectancy and single loss expectancy","Return on investment and total cost of ownership"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Recovery time objective and recovery point objective</strong> — the BIA's core output for each critical process is its RTO (how quickly it must be restored) and RPO (how much data loss is tolerable).<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Mean time between failures and mean time to repair</b>: are reliability engineering metrics for hardware, not BIA outputs.</span><span class='qd'><b>Annualized loss expectancy and single loss expectancy</b>: are quantitative risk assessment metrics, not the primary BIA continuity metrics.</span><span class='qd'><b>Return on investment and total cost of ownership</b>: are financial planning metrics unrelated to continuity requirements.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-029","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"hard","q":"A BIA reveals that Process A has an RTO of 4 hours and Process B has an RTO of 48 hours. During a recovery event with limited resources, which process should be prioritized first?","options":["Process B, because longer RTOs indicate greater business value","Both should be restored simultaneously regardless of RTO","Process A, because its shorter RTO indicates higher criticality and urgency","Neither; prioritization should be based solely on alphabetical order"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Process A, because its shorter RTO indicates higher criticality and urgency</strong> — a shorter RTO means the business can tolerate less downtime, signaling higher priority for recovery resource allocation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Process B, because longer RTOs indicate greater business value</b>: reverses the logic; a longer RTO means the process can wait longer, not that it is more valuable.</span><span class='qd'><b>Both should be restored simultaneously regardless of RTO</b>: ignores resource constraints stated in the scenario that require prioritization.</span><span class='qd'><b>Neither; prioritization should be based solely on alphabetical order</b>: is an arbitrary method disconnected from business impact data.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-030","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"hard","q":"A system has an RTO of 8 hours and an RPO of 1 hour. Backups currently run every 6 hours, and full restoration testing shows 10 hours to rebuild the system. What is the MOST significant gap revealed by this data?","options":["Only the RPO is at risk; RTO is comfortably met","Both the backup frequency and restoration time fail to meet their respective objectives","Only the RTO is at risk; RPO is comfortably met","There is no gap; both objectives are satisfied"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Both the backup frequency and restoration time fail to meet their respective objectives</strong> — a 6-hour backup interval exceeds the 1-hour RPO, and a 10-hour rebuild exceeds the 8-hour RTO, so both metrics are out of tolerance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Only the RPO is at risk; RTO is comfortably met</b>: ignores that the 10-hour restoration time also exceeds the 8-hour RTO.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only the RTO is at risk; RPO is comfortably met</b>: ignores that 6-hour backups exceed the 1-hour RPO.</span><span class='qd'><b>There is no gap; both objectives are satisfied</b>: contradicts the numbers given in the scenario.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-031","domain":4,"obj":"4B3","diff":"med","q":"Who typically holds ULTIMATE accountability for approving and funding the business continuity plan?","options":["The disaster recovery vendor","The incident response team lead","The help desk manager","Senior executive management"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Senior executive management</strong> — because BCP decisions involve enterprise-wide risk tolerance and funding commitments, ultimate accountability rests with senior management, who must approve and resource the plan.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The disaster recovery vendor</b>: provides services under contract but holds no organizational accountability for plan approval.</span><span class='qd'><b>The incident response team lead</b>: executes technical response but does not own enterprise BCP funding decisions.</span><span class='qd'><b>The help desk manager</b>: has an operational support role, not executive accountability for continuity planning.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-032","domain":4,"obj":"4B4","diff":"med","q":"A cold recovery site typically includes which of the following?","options":["Basic infrastructure such as power, cooling, and space, without pre-installed systems","Fully configured servers with real-time data replication","A dedicated staff on standby 24/7 at the site","Continuous synchronization with the production database"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Basic infrastructure such as power, cooling, and space, without pre-installed systems</strong> — a cold site provides only the physical facility shell; hardware, software, and data must be brought in and configured after activation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Fully configured servers with real-time data replication</b>: describes a hot site, not a cold site.</span><span class='qd'><b>A dedicated staff on standby 24/7 at the site</b>: is not a defining characteristic of a cold site, which is typically unstaffed until activated.</span><span class='qd'><b>Continuous synchronization with the production database</b>: describes hot-site capability, absent in a cold site.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-033","domain":4,"obj":"4A4","diff":"easy","q":"What is the PRIMARY goal of the containment phase in incident response?","options":["Permanently remove all traces of the attacker from the environment","Restore all systems to full production status","Limit the scope and impact of the incident before further damage occurs","Notify regulators of the breach"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Limit the scope and impact of the incident before further damage occurs</strong> — containment's purpose is to stop the incident from spreading or worsening while investigation continues.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Permanently remove all traces of the attacker from the environment</b>: describes eradication, a later phase.</span><span class='qd'><b>Restore all systems to full production status</b>: describes recovery, which follows eradication.</span><span class='qd'><b>Notify regulators of the breach</b>: is a communications/legal obligation, not the goal of containment itself.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-034","domain":4,"obj":"4A5","diff":"med","q":"After eradicating malware from a compromised server, the incident team wants to confirm no backdoors remain before returning the system to production. Which action BEST supports this objective?","options":["Immediately return the system to production to minimize downtime","Perform a thorough vulnerability scan and integrity check before reconnecting the system to the network","Skip verification since the malware was already removed","Rely solely on the antivirus scan that originally detected the malware"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Perform a thorough vulnerability scan and integrity check before reconnecting the system to the network</strong> — validating system integrity before restoration ensures no residual backdoors or vulnerabilities remain, reducing reinfection risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Immediately return the system to production to minimize downtime</b>: risks reintroducing a compromised system without verification.</span><span class='qd'><b>Skip verification since the malware was already removed</b>: is risky, since removal of known malware does not guarantee all backdoors are gone.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rely solely on the antivirus scan that originally detected the malware</b>: the same tool that missed the initial compromise may not catch residual artifacts.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-035","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"hard","q":"During evidence collection, an investigator wants to preserve the original storage media unaltered while still allowing analysis. What is the BEST practice to follow?","options":["Analyze the original drive directly to save time","Copy only the files that appear relevant to the investigation","Format the drive after backing up user documents","Create a forensically sound bit-for-bit image and analyze the copy, not the original"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Create a forensically sound bit-for-bit image and analyze the copy, not the original</strong> — a verified forensic image preserves the original evidence untouched while enabling thorough analysis on a working copy, maintaining evidentiary integrity.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Analyze the original drive directly to save time</b>: risks altering metadata or timestamps, compromising evidentiary integrity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Copy only the files that appear relevant to the investigation</b>: risks missing hidden or deleted data relevant to the case and does not preserve the full original state.</span><span class='qd'><b>Format the drive after backing up user documents</b>: destroys the original evidence entirely.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-036","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"med","q":"Place the following in the correct order of volatility, from MOST volatile to LEAST volatile: (1) hard disk data, (2) RAM contents, (3) CPU cache and registers, (4) backup archives.","options":["3, 2, 1, 4","1, 2, 3, 4","4, 1, 2, 3","2, 3, 1, 4"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>3, 2, 1, 4</strong> — CPU cache/registers are lost in nanoseconds, RAM is lost on power-down, disk persists until overwritten, and backup archives persist longest, so the correct volatility order is CPU registers, RAM, disk, then backups.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>1, 2, 3, 4</b>: incorrectly places disk before RAM and CPU registers, reversing the volatility order.</span><span class='qd'><b>4, 1, 2, 3</b>: places the least volatile item first, the opposite of correct sequencing.</span><span class='qd'><b>2, 3, 1, 4</b>: places RAM before CPU cache, which is actually more volatile than RAM.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-037","domain":4,"obj":"4A7","diff":"med","q":"Which stakeholder group is typically responsible for determining whether a breach notification legally must be sent to affected data subjects?","options":["The network operations team","The help desk","Legal counsel and privacy/compliance officers","The external managed security service provider"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Legal counsel and privacy/compliance officers</strong> — determining legal notification obligations requires interpreting applicable breach notification laws and regulations, a function of legal and compliance expertise.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The network operations team</b>: provides technical facts about the incident but does not make legal determinations.</span><span class='qd'><b>The help desk</b>: handles user-facing support tickets, not legal or regulatory analysis.</span><span class='qd'><b>The external managed security service provider</b>: may supply technical detection and response services but does not typically determine legal notification obligations.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-038","domain":4,"obj":"4A7","diff":"easy","q":"Effective incident communications planning should define escalation paths for which of the following audiences?","options":["Only the technical response team","Executive management, legal, regulators, customers, and media as applicable","Only the marketing department","Only external law enforcement"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Executive management, legal, regulators, customers, and media as applicable</strong> — a mature communications plan addresses the full range of internal and external stakeholders who may need timely, accurate information during an incident.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Only the technical response team</b>: is too narrow; many non-technical stakeholders have legitimate needs for incident information.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only the marketing department</b>: ignores critical audiences such as regulators and executive leadership.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only external law enforcement</b>: excludes internal stakeholders who require communication throughout the incident.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-039","domain":4,"obj":"4A8","diff":"med","q":"A SIEM generates a high volume of false-positive alerts, causing analyst fatigue. Which action would MOST effectively address this issue?","options":["Disable the SIEM until a replacement is procured","Ignore all alerts below critical severity permanently","Increase the number of analysts without changing detection logic","Tune correlation rules and thresholds based on the organization's actual environment and threat profile"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Tune correlation rules and thresholds based on the organization's actual environment and threat profile</strong> — proper tuning reduces noise by aligning detection logic with the real environment, improving signal-to-noise ratio without sacrificing detection capability.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Disable the SIEM until a replacement is procured</b>: eliminates detection capability entirely, a disproportionate response.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignore all alerts below critical severity permanently</b>: risks missing genuine incidents that do not initially register as critical.</span><span class='qd'><b>Increase the number of analysts without changing detection logic</b>: addresses symptoms with cost rather than fixing the underlying noise problem.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-040","domain":4,"obj":"4A9","diff":"med","q":"Which metric BEST demonstrates the maturity improvement of an incident response program over time?","options":["Trending mean time to detect and mean time to respond across multiple incidents","The total number of security tools purchased","The number of employees in the security department","The length of the incident response plan document"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Trending mean time to detect and mean time to respond across multiple incidents</strong> — tracking these metrics over time objectively shows whether detection and response capabilities are actually improving.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The total number of security tools purchased</b>: tool count does not equate to improved response capability.</span><span class='qd'><b>The number of employees in the security department</b>: headcount alone does not measure effectiveness.</span><span class='qd'><b>The length of the incident response plan document</b>: document length has no bearing on actual response maturity.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-041","domain":4,"obj":"4B5","diff":"med","q":"A parallel recovery test is conducted for a critical financial system. What distinguishes this test from a full interruption test?","options":["Production systems are fully shut down during the test","Only documentation is reviewed, with no systems activated","The recovery site is activated and validated while production systems continue normal operation","The test is conducted without informing any stakeholders"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The recovery site is activated and validated while production systems continue normal operation</strong> — a parallel test proves the recovery environment functions correctly without disrupting live production, unlike a full interruption test.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Production systems are fully shut down during the test</b>: describes a full interruption test, not a parallel test.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only documentation is reviewed, with no systems activated</b>: describes a tabletop or checklist review, not a parallel test.</span><span class='qd'><b>The test is conducted without informing any stakeholders</b>: contradicts sound test management practice, which requires planning and stakeholder awareness.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-042","domain":4,"obj":"4B6","diff":"easy","q":"Which term refers to the absolute maximum amount of time a business process can be unavailable before causing unacceptable consequences to the organization?","options":["Recovery point objective (RPO)","Maximum tolerable downtime (MTD)","Service level agreement (SLA)","Mean time to repair (MTTR)"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Maximum tolerable downtime (MTD)</strong> — MTD represents the outer limit of acceptable downtime for a process before consequences become unacceptable to the organization, encompassing RTO and any additional work-recovery time.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Recovery point objective (RPO)</b>: measures tolerable data loss, not overall downtime duration.</span><span class='qd'><b>Service level agreement (SLA)</b>: is a contractual performance commitment, not the internal downtime tolerance threshold.</span><span class='qd'><b>Mean time to repair (MTTR)</b>: is an average repair-time metric, not a maximum tolerance threshold.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-043","domain":4,"obj":"4B6","diff":"hard","q":"A process has an MTD of 24 hours. The RTO for restoring the technical systems is 18 hours, and work-recovery time (resuming manual processing, data re-entry, etc.) after systems are restored is estimated at 8 hours. What does this analysis reveal?","options":["The plan comfortably meets the MTD with 6 hours to spare","RPO must be recalculated before RTO can be assessed","MTD is irrelevant once RTO has been defined","The combined RTO and work-recovery time of 26 hours exceeds the 24-hour MTD, indicating a gap"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The combined RTO and work-recovery time of 26 hours exceeds the 24-hour MTD, indicating a gap</strong> — since MTD must accommodate both technical restoration and work-recovery time, 18+8=26 hours exceeds the 24-hour tolerance, revealing a planning gap that must be closed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The plan comfortably meets the MTD with 6 hours to spare</b>: miscalculates the total; 18+8 hours exceeds, not falls under, 24 hours.</span><span class='qd'><b>RPO must be recalculated before RTO can be assessed</b>: RPO addresses data loss, a separate concern from the downtime/MTD analysis presented.</span><span class='qd'><b>MTD is irrelevant once RTO has been defined</b>: incorrectly dismisses MTD, which is the ultimate constraint RTO and work-recovery time must together satisfy.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-044","domain":4,"obj":"4B7","diff":"med","q":"Which role is PRIMARILY responsible for declaring a disaster and formally activating the disaster recovery plan?","options":["A predefined crisis management or executive authority named in the plan","Any employee who first notices the outage","The recovery site facility manager","The organization's external auditor"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A predefined crisis management or executive authority named in the plan</strong> — disaster declaration authority should be clearly assigned in advance to a specific role or crisis management team to avoid delay or confusion during an actual event.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Any employee who first notices the outage</b>: lacks the authority and full situational context needed to make a formal declaration.</span><span class='qd'><b>The recovery site facility manager</b>: manages the physical site but does not typically hold declaration authority.</span><span class='qd'><b>The organization's external auditor</b>: reviews controls and compliance but has no operational role in declaring a disaster.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-045","domain":4,"obj":"4B8","diff":"med","q":"Which activity should occur immediately after a disaster recovery plan is tested and gaps are identified?","options":["Discard the test results, since the plan already exists","Wait until the next annual review cycle to make changes","Update the plan and retrain personnel based on lessons learned","Terminate the DR program, since testing revealed weaknesses"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Update the plan and retrain personnel based on lessons learned</strong> — testing exists to reveal gaps so the plan can be improved promptly; identified deficiencies should be remediated and communicated through updated procedures and training.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Discard the test results, since the plan already exists</b>: wastes the value of testing and leaves known gaps unaddressed.</span><span class='qd'><b>Wait until the next annual review cycle to make changes</b>: unnecessarily delays fixing known deficiencies that could cause real failures.</span><span class='qd'><b>Terminate the DR program, since testing revealed weaknesses</b>: is a disproportionate reaction; testing findings should drive improvement, not program cancellation.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-046","domain":4,"obj":"4A1","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following is a KEY benefit of having a documented and approved incident response plan before an incident occurs?","options":["It eliminates the possibility of future incidents","It reduces response time and confusion by pre-defining roles and procedures","It replaces the need for security awareness training","It guarantees regulatory compliance automatically"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>It reduces response time and confusion by pre-defining roles and procedures</strong> — a documented plan ensures responders know their roles and the sequence of actions in advance, reducing delay and error under pressure.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It eliminates the possibility of future incidents</b>: no plan can prevent all incidents; the plan governs response, not prevention.</span><span class='qd'><b>It replaces the need for security awareness training</b>: awareness training and incident response planning serve different, complementary purposes.</span><span class='qd'><b>It guarantees regulatory compliance automatically</b>: having a plan supports compliance efforts but does not by itself guarantee compliance.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-047","domain":4,"obj":"4A2","diff":"easy","q":"Which NIST 800-61 phase includes activities such as establishing communication procedures, training the response team, and acquiring necessary tools BEFORE any incident occurs?","options":["Detection & Analysis","Containment, Eradication & Recovery","Post-Incident Activity","Preparation"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Preparation</strong> — this foundational phase builds the capability (tools, training, communication plans) needed to respond effectively once an incident occurs.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Detection & Analysis</b>: focuses on identifying and scoping incidents once they occur, not pre-incident readiness.</span><span class='qd'><b>Containment, Eradication & Recovery</b>: occurs during active incident handling, not beforehand.</span><span class='qd'><b>Post-Incident Activity</b>: occurs after the incident concludes, focused on lessons learned.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-048","domain":4,"obj":"4A3","diff":"hard","q":"An organization's severity matrix classifies incidents by combining which two dimensions?","options":["Impact and urgency","Cost and vendor reputation","Number of affected users only","Time zone and detection tool"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Impact and urgency</strong> — a well-designed severity matrix weighs both the magnitude of business impact and the time-sensitivity of the response required, producing a prioritized classification.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Cost and vendor reputation</b>: vendor reputation is not a standard classification dimension for incident severity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Number of affected users only</b>: is a single data point, not a complete two-dimensional severity model.</span><span class='qd'><b>Time zone and detection tool</b>: are operational details unrelated to severity classification logic.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-049","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"med","q":"Which stakeholders should be interviewed during a business impact analysis to accurately capture recovery requirements?","options":["Only the IT infrastructure team","Only external auditors","Business process owners across critical functions","Only the physical security team"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Business process owners across critical functions</strong> — process owners best understand the operational, financial, and reputational impact of downtime for their specific functions, making their input essential to an accurate BIA.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Only the IT infrastructure team</b>: has technical insight but lacks full visibility into business-side impact and priorities.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only external auditors</b>: provide independent assurance but are not the source of operational impact data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only the physical security team</b>: focuses on facility security, not business process impact.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-050","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"easy","q":"If an organization decides it can tolerate losing up to 15 minutes of transaction data, which metric is being defined?","options":["Recovery time objective (RTO)","Recovery point objective (RPO)","Maximum tolerable downtime (MTD)","Service level objective (SLO) for uptime"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Recovery point objective (RPO)</strong> — RPO specifically expresses the acceptable amount of data loss measured as a time interval, matching the 15-minute tolerance described.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Recovery time objective (RTO)</b>: measures acceptable downtime duration for restoring service, not data loss tolerance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Maximum tolerable downtime (MTD)</b>: represents the outer limit of total acceptable downtime, not data-loss tolerance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Service level objective (SLO) for uptime</b>: measures availability targets, not data-loss tolerance.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-051","domain":4,"obj":"4B3","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the relationship between the incident response plan and the business continuity plan?","options":["The IRP always supersedes the BCP","The BCP is only used for natural disasters, never for cyber incidents","They are entirely unrelated and never interact","The IRP may trigger BCP activation if the incident escalates into a significant business disruption"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The IRP may trigger BCP activation if the incident escalates into a significant business disruption</strong> — a severe cyber incident (e.g., ransomware crippling operations) can cross the threshold from a security incident into a business continuity event, triggering BCP activation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The IRP always supersedes the BCP</b>: incorrectly implies a fixed hierarchy rather than situational escalation.</span><span class='qd'><b>The BCP is only used for natural disasters, never for cyber incidents</b>: is inaccurate; modern BCPs commonly address cyber-driven disruptions as a trigger.</span><span class='qd'><b>They are entirely unrelated and never interact</b>: contradicts the well-established escalation relationship between incident response and continuity planning.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-052","domain":4,"obj":"4B4","diff":"med","q":"Which recovery site option is generally MOST cost-effective but requires the LONGEST time to become operational?","options":["Cold site","Hot site","Warm site","Reciprocal hot site with real-time replication"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Cold site</strong> — cold sites have the lowest ongoing cost because they lack pre-installed systems, but this also means they require the most time and effort to become operational after activation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Hot site</b>: is the fastest to activate but also the most expensive to maintain continuously.</span><span class='qd'><b>Warm site</b>: falls between cold and hot in both cost and activation time.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reciprocal hot site with real-time replication</b>: still implies hot-site-level readiness and cost, not the cheapest, slowest option.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-053","domain":4,"obj":"4A4","diff":"med","q":"Why is it important to document all containment actions taken during an incident, even if they are later reversed?","options":["Because documentation is required only for regulatory audits","Because containment actions are irrelevant to the final report","To support post-incident review, legal defensibility, and understanding of the incident timeline","To satisfy vendor support contract requirements only"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>To support post-incident review, legal defensibility, and understanding of the incident timeline</strong> — thorough documentation of every action taken, including reversed ones, preserves an accurate record essential for lessons learned, potential legal proceedings, and reconstructing the incident timeline.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Because documentation is required only for regulatory audits</b>: understates the broader operational and legal value of documentation beyond audits.</span><span class='qd'><b>Because containment actions are irrelevant to the final report</b>: is incorrect; containment actions are a core part of the incident narrative.</span><span class='qd'><b>To satisfy vendor support contract requirements only</b>: is far too narrow a justification for comprehensive incident documentation.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-054","domain":4,"obj":"4A5","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following is the correct sequence of activities within eradication and recovery?","options":["Restore systems first, then determine the root cause afterward","Remove the root cause, patch vulnerabilities, then restore systems and monitor for recurrence","Notify customers, then eradicate the threat","Close the incident ticket, then begin eradication"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Remove the root cause, patch vulnerabilities, then restore systems and monitor for recurrence</strong> — proper sequencing eliminates the threat and closes the vulnerability before returning systems to production, followed by heightened monitoring to catch any recurrence.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Restore systems first, then determine the root cause afterward</b>: risks reintroducing the same compromise before the cause is understood and fixed.</span><span class='qd'><b>Notify customers, then eradicate the threat</b>: reverses priority; technical remediation should not wait on communications.</span><span class='qd'><b>Close the incident ticket, then begin eradication</b>: prematurely closes the incident before the technical work is even performed.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-055","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"med","q":"Why should an investigator use a write-blocker when acquiring evidence from a hard drive?","options":["To speed up the imaging process significantly","To automatically encrypt the acquired image","To bypass the need for a chain-of-custody log","To prevent any modification to the original media during the imaging process"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>To prevent any modification to the original media during the imaging process</strong> — a write-blocker ensures the acquisition process is read-only, preserving the original evidence's integrity for legal and forensic purposes.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To speed up the imaging process significantly</b>: write-blockers do not meaningfully accelerate imaging; their purpose is integrity, not speed.</span><span class='qd'><b>To automatically encrypt the acquired image</b>: encryption is a separate consideration, not a function of a write-blocker.</span><span class='qd'><b>To bypass the need for a chain-of-custody log</b>: a write-blocker does not eliminate the ongoing requirement to document custody.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-056","domain":4,"obj":"4A7","diff":"med","q":"A breach involves a third-party payment processor that handles credit card data on the organization's behalf. Who is generally responsible for making the initial determination of notification obligations under most breach laws?","options":["The organization that owns the customer relationship, in coordination with the processor's contractual obligations","The payment processor alone, with no involvement from the primary organization","The customers themselves, who must self-report suspected fraud","No one, since the third party is solely liable"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The organization that owns the customer relationship, in coordination with the processor's contractual obligations</strong> — the data controller typically retains notification responsibility to affected individuals and regulators, though contracts may define processor obligations to assist or notify the controller promptly.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The payment processor alone, with no involvement from the primary organization</b>: ignores the controller's typical legal responsibility for its customers' data.</span><span class='qd'><b>The customers themselves, who must self-report suspected fraud</b>: shifts an organizational obligation onto individuals incorrectly.</span><span class='qd'><b>No one, since the third party is solely liable</b>: is inconsistent with how most breach notification laws allocate controller responsibility.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-057","domain":4,"obj":"4A8","diff":"hard","q":"An organization is evaluating whether to implement SOAR in addition to its existing SIEM. Which scenario BEST justifies this investment?","options":["The organization has no logging infrastructure at all","The organization wants to eliminate its incident response team entirely","Analysts spend excessive time manually performing repetitive triage and containment steps for common alert types","The SIEM already fully automates every response action needed"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Analysts spend excessive time manually performing repetitive triage and containment steps for common alert types</strong> — SOAR delivers the greatest value by automating well-understood, repetitive workflows, freeing analysts for higher-value investigative work.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The organization has no logging infrastructure at all</b>: SOAR depends on data from a SIEM or similar sources; without logging, foundational detection capability is missing first.</span><span class='qd'><b>The organization wants to eliminate its incident response team entirely</b>: SOAR augments analyst capability rather than replacing human judgment entirely.</span><span class='qd'><b>The SIEM already fully automates every response action needed</b>: if this were true, there would be no gap for SOAR to address.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-058","domain":4,"obj":"4A9","diff":"easy","q":"What is the PRIMARY purpose of a lessons-learned session after a major incident?","options":["To assign blame to individuals responsible for the incident","To identify root causes and improve future prevention and response processes","To close out the incident ticket for reporting purposes only","To satisfy a purely ceremonial requirement with no real output"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>To identify root causes and improve future prevention and response processes</strong> — the lessons-learned session drives continuous improvement by objectively analyzing what happened and what should change going forward.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To assign blame to individuals responsible for the incident</b>: a blame-focused approach discourages open reporting and undermines the improvement purpose of the session.</span><span class='qd'><b>To close out the incident ticket for reporting purposes only</b>: understates the substantive value of analysis beyond simple ticket closure.</span><span class='qd'><b>To satisfy a purely ceremonial requirement with no real output</b>: contradicts the intended, actionable purpose of the session.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-059","domain":4,"obj":"4B5","diff":"easy","q":"Which type of test involves activating the actual recovery site and verifying its systems function correctly, while the primary site continues normal production?","options":["Full interruption test","Tabletop exercise","Plan review","Parallel test"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Parallel test</strong> — this test validates the recovery environment's actual functionality without disrupting live production operations.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Full interruption test</b>: shifts actual production operations to the recovery site, unlike a parallel test.</span><span class='qd'><b>Tabletop exercise</b>: is a discussion-based walkthrough with no system activation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Plan review</b>: is a documentation review with no system testing involved.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-060","domain":4,"obj":"4B6","diff":"med","q":"Which relationship among RTO, RPO, and MTD is generally correct?","options":["RTO should be less than or equal to MTD, since MTD represents the outer boundary of tolerable downtime","MTD is always shorter than RTO","RPO must always exceed RTO","RTO and RPO must always be numerically equal"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>RTO should be less than or equal to MTD, since MTD represents the outer boundary of tolerable downtime</strong> — RTO is a planning target that must fit within the MTD ceiling; exceeding MTD means the organization suffers unacceptable consequences.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>MTD is always shorter than RTO</b>: reverses the correct relationship; RTO must fit within MTD, not exceed it.</span><span class='qd'><b>RPO must always exceed RTO</b>: there is no fixed rule requiring this relationship; RPO and RTO address different dimensions (data loss vs. downtime).</span><span class='qd'><b>RTO and RPO must always be numerically equal</b>: they are independent metrics addressing different risks and need not match numerically.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-061","domain":4,"obj":"4B7","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following is a critical success factor for effective crisis communication during a declared disaster?","options":["Allowing every employee to speak to media independently","Withholding all information until the crisis is fully resolved","Designating a single authoritative spokesperson and consistent messaging channel","Communicating only through unofficial social media accounts"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Designating a single authoritative spokesperson and consistent messaging channel</strong> — centralizing communications prevents conflicting or inaccurate statements and maintains stakeholder trust during a crisis.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Allowing every employee to speak to media independently</b>: risks inconsistent, inaccurate, or unauthorized statements.</span><span class='qd'><b>Withholding all information until the crisis is fully resolved</b>: can damage trust and may violate notification obligations requiring timely updates.</span><span class='qd'><b>Communicating only through unofficial social media accounts</b>: lacks authority and control, risking misinformation.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-062","domain":4,"obj":"4B8","diff":"med","q":"Why should DR and BC plans be reviewed and updated on a regular, defined cycle rather than only after an incident?","options":["Regular review is only a regulatory formality with no practical value","Business processes, technology, and personnel change continuously, and outdated plans may fail during a real event","Plans never need updates once initially approved","Only annual full-interruption tests are considered valid maintenance"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Business processes, technology, and personnel change continuously, and outdated plans may fail during a real event</strong> — organizational change is constant, so plans must be periodically revalidated to remain accurate and effective when actually needed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Regular review is only a regulatory formality with no practical value</b>: dismisses the genuine operational risk of outdated plans.</span><span class='qd'><b>Plans never need updates once initially approved</b>: is factually incorrect and dangerous, given ongoing organizational change.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only annual full-interruption tests are considered valid maintenance</b>: incorrectly excludes other valid maintenance activities like tabletop exercises and plan reviews.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-063","domain":4,"obj":"4A1","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the role of an information security manager during a major incident, as opposed to the technical responders?","options":["Personally performing all forensic disk imaging","Writing all antivirus signatures used during the response","Configuring firewall rules directly on every affected device","Providing overall coordination, resource allocation, and communication with executive leadership"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Providing overall coordination, resource allocation, and communication with executive leadership</strong> — the security manager's role is primarily coordinative and strategic, ensuring resources are allocated and leadership is informed, while technical responders execute hands-on tasks.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Personally performing all forensic disk imaging</b>: is a hands-on technical task typically performed by trained forensic specialists, not the manager's core role.</span><span class='qd'><b>Writing all antivirus signatures used during the response</b>: is a specialized technical task outside the manager's coordinative function.</span><span class='qd'><b>Configuring firewall rules directly on every affected device</b>: is an operational task for network/security engineers, not the manager's primary duty.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-064","domain":4,"obj":"4A2","diff":"med","q":"An organization's SOC detects anomalous authentication attempts against a domain controller. Analysis is underway to determine scope and impact. Which NIST 800-61 phase is currently in progress?","options":["Detection & Analysis","Preparation","Eradication","Post-Incident Activity"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Detection & Analysis</strong> — actively analyzing anomalous activity to determine scope and impact is the defining activity of this phase.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Preparation</b>: precedes any actual incident activity; this scenario describes an active investigation already underway.</span><span class='qd'><b>Eradication</b>: involves removing the confirmed root cause, which requires the analysis phase to be complete first.</span><span class='qd'><b>Post-Incident Activity</b>: occurs after the incident has been resolved, not during active analysis.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-065","domain":4,"obj":"4A3","diff":"easy","q":"Why is timely and accurate incident triage important?","options":["It eliminates the need for a formal incident response plan","It guarantees no further incidents will occur","It ensures limited resources are directed toward the incidents with the greatest business impact first","It automatically satisfies all breach notification laws"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>It ensures limited resources are directed toward the incidents with the greatest business impact first</strong> — effective triage prioritizes response effort according to actual risk and impact, making the best use of constrained resources.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It eliminates the need for a formal incident response plan</b>: triage is a component within the plan, not a replacement for it.</span><span class='qd'><b>It guarantees no further incidents will occur</b>: triage manages response, not prevention of future incidents.</span><span class='qd'><b>It automatically satisfies all breach notification laws</b>: legal notification requires separate, deliberate compliance action.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-066","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"med","q":"A BIA identifies that a payroll processing system, if down for more than 3 business days, will result in missed regulatory filings and employee dissatisfaction. This finding is used to establish which value?","options":["The annual loss expectancy for payroll fraud","The recovery time objective for the payroll system","The single loss expectancy for a data breach","The mean time between failures for payroll hardware"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The recovery time objective for the payroll system</strong> — the BIA finding directly establishes how long the process can be down before unacceptable consequences occur, which defines the RTO.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The annual loss expectancy for payroll fraud</b>: is a quantitative risk metric related to fraud risk, not downtime tolerance.</span><span class='qd'><b>The single loss expectancy for a data breach</b>: relates to a specific breach risk calculation, not downtime tolerance.</span><span class='qd'><b>The mean time between failures for payroll hardware</b>: is a hardware reliability metric unrelated to business impact findings.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-067","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"med","q":"An organization sets an RPO of zero for its core financial ledger. What technical capability is generally required to meet this objective?","options":["Nightly tape backups shipped offsite weekly","Manual data re-entry procedures after an outage","Quarterly full backups only","Synchronous, real-time data replication to a secondary location"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Synchronous, real-time data replication to a secondary location</strong> — an RPO of zero requires that no committed transaction can be lost, which is only achievable through continuous, synchronous replication.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Nightly tape backups shipped offsite weekly</b>: would result in up to a week of potential data loss, far exceeding a zero RPO.</span><span class='qd'><b>Manual data re-entry procedures after an outage</b>: is error-prone and cannot guarantee zero data loss.</span><span class='qd'><b>Quarterly full backups only</b>: would allow months of data loss, incompatible with a zero RPO.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-068","domain":4,"obj":"4B3","diff":"easy","q":"Which plan specifically addresses how employees will continue performing critical manual or interim processes while IT systems are being restored?","options":["Business continuity plan","Disaster recovery plan","Vulnerability management plan","Change management plan"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Business continuity plan</strong> — the BCP covers continuity of business operations broadly, including manual workarounds and interim processes, while systems are being restored under the DRP.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Disaster recovery plan</b>: focuses specifically on restoring IT systems and infrastructure, not manual business workaround procedures.</span><span class='qd'><b>Vulnerability management plan</b>: governs identification and remediation of technical vulnerabilities, unrelated to continuity procedures.</span><span class='qd'><b>Change management plan</b>: governs authorized changes to systems, unrelated to business continuity during outages.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-069","domain":4,"obj":"4B4","diff":"hard","q":"Two organizations in different industries agree to provide each other backup processing capacity in the event either suffers a disaster. What is this arrangement called, and what is a KEY risk associated with it?","options":["Hot site contract; the risk is excessive ongoing cost","Cold site lease; the risk is lack of any physical facility","Reciprocal agreement; the risk is that both organizations may need capacity simultaneously during a shared regional disaster","Mobile site rental; the risk is limited transportability"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Reciprocal agreement; the risk is that both organizations may need capacity simultaneously during a shared regional disaster</strong> — reciprocal agreements are cost-effective but carry the risk that a widespread event (e.g., a regional disaster) could affect both parties at once, leaving neither able to help the other.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Hot site contract; the risk is excessive ongoing cost</b>: mischaracterizes the arrangement as a hot site rather than a mutual reciprocal agreement.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cold site lease; the risk is lack of any physical facility</b>: the scenario is not a leased facility but a mutual arrangement between peer organizations.</span><span class='qd'><b>Mobile site rental; the risk is limited transportability</b>: does not match the described peer-to-peer capacity-sharing scenario.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-070","domain":4,"obj":"4A4","diff":"easy","q":"Which action is an example of an IMMEDIATE, short-term containment measure?","options":["Rebuilding the operating system from a verified clean image","Disconnecting an infected workstation from the network","Conducting a full root-cause forensic investigation","Issuing a public statement about the incident"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Disconnecting an infected workstation from the network</strong> — this is a fast, immediate action taken to stop further spread while more thorough analysis and remediation proceed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Rebuilding the operating system from a verified clean image</b>: is an eradication/recovery action, occurring after containment and root-cause determination.</span><span class='qd'><b>Conducting a full root-cause forensic investigation</b>: is a detection/analysis activity, typically more time-consuming than immediate containment.</span><span class='qd'><b>Issuing a public statement about the incident</b>: is a communications activity, not a technical containment measure.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-071","domain":4,"obj":"4A5","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following is generally considered part of the recovery phase rather than the eradication phase?","options":["Removing malware executables and disabling compromised accounts","Identifying and patching the exploited vulnerability","Deleting attacker-created backdoor accounts","Restoring systems from clean backups and returning them to production with enhanced monitoring"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Restoring systems from clean backups and returning them to production with enhanced monitoring</strong> — recovery focuses on returning systems to normal operation and closely monitoring for recurrence, following eradication of the root cause.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Removing malware executables and disabling compromised accounts</b>: is an eradication activity, removing the threat itself.</span><span class='qd'><b>Identifying and patching the exploited vulnerability</b>: is also part of eradication, closing the attack vector.</span><span class='qd'><b>Deleting attacker-created backdoor accounts</b>: is an eradication task removing persistence mechanisms.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-072","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"med","q":"An investigator documents the exact time, date, and personnel involved every time evidence changes hands. What forensic requirement does this satisfy?","options":["Chain of custody","Order of volatility","Least privilege","Non-repudiation of transactions"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Chain of custody</strong> — meticulously logging every transfer, access, and handling of evidence establishes an auditable chain of custody, critical to admissibility.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Order of volatility</b>: concerns the sequence of evidence collection based on how quickly data degrades, not custody tracking.</span><span class='qd'><b>Least privilege</b>: is an access control principle unrelated to evidence handling records.</span><span class='qd'><b>Non-repudiation of transactions</b>: relates to proving the origin of a digital transaction, not physical/digital evidence custody tracking.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-073","domain":4,"obj":"4A7","diff":"hard","q":"A breach affects both EU residents (subject to GDPR) and residents of a U.S. state with its own breach notification law with a 30-day deadline. How should the organization approach notification timing?","options":["Wait 30 days and issue a single combined notification to all affected parties","Notify only under the law of the country where the organization is headquartered","Comply with the most stringent applicable deadline, which in this case is the GDPR's 72-hour requirement","Choose the deadline that is most convenient operationally, regardless of jurisdiction"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Comply with the most stringent applicable deadline, which in this case is the GDPR's 72-hour requirement</strong> — when multiple jurisdictions apply, an organization must meet each applicable law's requirements, effectively defaulting to the strictest timeline to remain compliant everywhere.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Wait 30 days and issue a single combined notification to all affected parties</b>: would violate the GDPR's shorter 72-hour requirement for the EU residents affected.</span><span class='qd'><b>Notify only under the law of the country where the organization is headquartered</b>: ignores the extraterritorial reach of GDPR and other applicable laws based on where data subjects reside.</span><span class='qd'><b>Choose the deadline that is most convenient operationally, regardless of jurisdiction</b>: disregards legal obligations in favor of convenience, risking noncompliance.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-074","domain":4,"obj":"4A8","diff":"med","q":"Which capability allows a SOC to automatically enrich an alert with threat intelligence context, such as known malicious IP reputation, before an analyst reviews it?","options":["A basic firewall access control list","SOAR playbook integration with threat intelligence feeds","A manual spreadsheet tracking indicators of compromise","An annual penetration test report"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>SOAR playbook integration with threat intelligence feeds</strong> — SOAR platforms can automatically query threat intelligence sources and attach contextual enrichment to alerts before human review, accelerating triage.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A basic firewall access control list</b>: enforces static traffic rules and does not perform dynamic alert enrichment.</span><span class='qd'><b>A manual spreadsheet tracking indicators of compromise</b>: is a manual, non-automated process, slower and more error-prone than automated enrichment.</span><span class='qd'><b>An annual penetration test report</b>: is a point-in-time assessment document, not a real-time enrichment capability.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-075","domain":4,"obj":"4A9","diff":"med","q":"After a post-incident review, the team identifies that detection took far longer than acceptable due to a logging gap on a critical server. What should happen NEXT?","options":["Simply note the finding in a report with no further action","Wait for the next major incident to reassess logging coverage","Remove the server from the network permanently","Update the IRP and technical controls to close the logging gap and track the remediation to completion"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Update the IRP and technical controls to close the logging gap and track the remediation to completion</strong> — lessons learned must translate into tracked, actionable remediation to genuinely close identified gaps, not remain as unaddressed findings.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Simply note the finding in a report with no further action</b>: fails to remediate the identified weakness, leaving the organization exposed to a repeat failure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Wait for the next major incident to reassess logging coverage</b>: unnecessarily delays a known and identified fix.</span><span class='qd'><b>Remove the server from the network permanently</b>: is a disproportionate response to a logging deficiency, likely disrupting business operations unnecessarily.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-076","domain":4,"obj":"4B5","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following is a key advantage of conducting regular tabletop exercises even though they do not test actual system failover?","options":["They validate roles, communication paths, and decision-making at low cost and risk","They provide definitive proof that all systems will fail over successfully","They eliminate the need for any other form of DR/BC testing","They are legally required in every jurisdiction regardless of industry"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>They validate roles, communication paths, and decision-making at low cost and risk</strong> — tabletop exercises efficiently surface gaps in plans, roles, and communication without the cost or risk of a live failover, making them valuable even though they do not test technical recovery directly.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>They provide definitive proof that all systems will fail over successfully</b>: only a live test (parallel or full interruption) can validate actual technical failover.</span><span class='qd'><b>They eliminate the need for any other form of DR/BC testing</b>: a mature testing program uses multiple test types, not tabletop exercises alone.</span><span class='qd'><b>They are legally required in every jurisdiction regardless of industry</b>: overstates a universal legal mandate that does not uniformly exist.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-077","domain":4,"obj":"4B6","diff":"med","q":"A retailer determines that its point-of-sale system can be down for at most 2 hours before daily revenue loss becomes catastrophic, factoring in both technical restoration and manual workaround limitations. This 2-hour figure represents which value?","options":["Recovery point objective (RPO) only","Mean time to detect (MTTD)","Maximum tolerable downtime (MTD)","Service level agreement penalty threshold"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Maximum tolerable downtime (MTD)</strong> — because the figure accounts for the total combined tolerance including both technical restoration and workaround limitations, it represents the overarching MTD, not merely a component RTO.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Recovery point objective (RPO) only</b>: RPO addresses data loss tolerance, not overall downtime tolerance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Mean time to detect (MTTD)</b>: measures how quickly incidents are detected, unrelated to downtime tolerance thresholds.</span><span class='qd'><b>Service level agreement penalty threshold</b>: is a contractual term, not necessarily aligned with the organization's internal MTD calculation.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-078","domain":4,"obj":"4B7","diff":"easy","q":"Which team is typically responsible for making high-level strategic decisions during a declared disaster, such as resource allocation and stakeholder communication priorities?","options":["Server administration team","Crisis management team","Help desk tier 1 support","Network cabling contractors"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Crisis management team</strong> — this group provides strategic oversight, decision-making authority, and coordination across the organization during a declared disaster.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Server administration team</b>: executes technical recovery tasks, not strategic organizational decisions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Help desk tier 1 support</b>: handles routine user support requests, not crisis-level strategic decisions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Network cabling contractors</b>: perform physical infrastructure work, unrelated to strategic crisis decisions.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-079","domain":4,"obj":"4B8","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following should trigger an unscheduled review and update of the business continuity plan, outside the normal review cycle?","options":["A routine software patch applied to a non-critical workstation","A minor change to the office break room layout","An employee's approved vacation request","A significant merger, acquisition, or major change to critical business processes"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A significant merger, acquisition, or major change to critical business processes</strong> — major organizational changes can invalidate existing continuity assumptions and dependencies, warranting an immediate plan review rather than waiting for the next scheduled cycle.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A routine software patch applied to a non-critical workstation</b>: is a minor operational change unlikely to materially affect continuity planning.</span><span class='qd'><b>A minor change to the office break room layout</b>: has no bearing on business continuity requirements.</span><span class='qd'><b>An employee's approved vacation request</b>: is a routine HR matter, not a trigger for plan revision.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-080","domain":4,"obj":"4A1","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following BEST justifies conducting regular incident response tabletop exercises with executive management, not just technical staff?","options":["Executives must understand their decision-making role and be comfortable exercising authority during a real incident","Executives are legally required to perform all technical remediation steps","Technical staff no longer need training once executives are included","Tabletop exercises are only meaningful when executives are absent"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Executives must understand their decision-making role and be comfortable exercising authority during a real incident</strong> — executive involvement in exercises ensures leadership is prepared to make timely, informed decisions (e.g., disclosure, resource authorization) when a real incident occurs.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Executives are legally required to perform all technical remediation steps</b>: technical remediation is performed by technical staff, not executives.</span><span class='qd'><b>Technical staff no longer need training once executives are included</b>: both groups require ongoing training; one does not replace the other.</span><span class='qd'><b>Tabletop exercises are only meaningful when executives are absent</b>: contradicts the value of cross-functional participation including leadership.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-081","domain":4,"obj":"4A2","diff":"med","q":"During the detection and analysis phase, an analyst must determine both the scope of affected systems and the incident's likely business impact. Which activity BEST supports accurate scoping?","options":["Immediately restoring the most critical business system from backup","Issuing a public press release with preliminary findings","Correlating logs, network traffic, and endpoint data across the environment","Disabling the incident response plan for future updates"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Correlating logs, network traffic, and endpoint data across the environment</strong> — comprehensive correlation across multiple data sources is essential to accurately determine the true scope of an incident during analysis.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Immediately restoring the most critical business system from backup</b>: is premature recovery action taken before scope and root cause are understood.</span><span class='qd'><b>Issuing a public press release with preliminary findings</b>: is a communications action, not a scoping/analysis activity, and premature disclosure carries its own risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling the incident response plan for future updates</b>: is nonsensical during active incident handling.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-082","domain":4,"obj":"4A3","diff":"med","q":"Two incidents are reported simultaneously: one is a phishing email reported by a single employee with no evidence of compromise, and the other is confirmed ransomware encrypting files on a file server. Applying triage principles, which should be addressed FIRST?","options":["The phishing email, because it was reported first","The confirmed ransomware incident, due to its immediate and severe business impact","Both should be assigned to the same analyst simultaneously with equal priority","Neither should be prioritized; incidents should be handled in the order received"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The confirmed ransomware incident, due to its immediate and severe business impact</strong> — triage prioritizes by actual and potential business impact; active ransomware encrypting files represents a severe, ongoing threat requiring immediate attention over an unconfirmed phishing report.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The phishing email, because it was reported first</b>: order of reporting does not reflect actual severity or business impact.</span><span class='qd'><b>Both should be assigned to the same analyst simultaneously with equal priority</b>: fails to reflect the vastly different urgency levels between a confirmed active attack and an unconfirmed report.</span><span class='qd'><b>Neither should be prioritized; incidents should be handled in the order received</b>: ignores the fundamental purpose of severity-based triage.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-083","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"med","q":"Which output of the BIA is used directly to justify the investment level in disaster recovery infrastructure, such as a hot versus cold site?","options":["The organization's annual marketing budget","The number of help desk tickets opened per month","The physical square footage of the primary data center","The criticality ranking and recovery time objectives of business processes"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The criticality ranking and recovery time objectives of business processes</strong> — BIA-derived criticality and RTOs directly inform how much investment in recovery infrastructure (e.g., hot vs. cold site) is justified for each process.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The organization's annual marketing budget</b>: is unrelated to disaster recovery infrastructure investment decisions.</span><span class='qd'><b>The number of help desk tickets opened per month</b>: reflects support volume, not business criticality or recovery requirements.</span><span class='qd'><b>The physical square footage of the primary data center</b>: is a facility attribute, not a BIA-derived business impact metric.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-084","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following would DIRECTLY help an organization reduce its RPO for a critical database?","options":["Increasing the frequency of data replication or backups","Increasing the number of help desk staff","Extending the vendor support contract","Reducing the number of firewall rules"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Increasing the frequency of data replication or backups</strong> — more frequent replication or backup intervals directly shrink the potential data-loss window, thereby reducing RPO.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Increasing the number of help desk staff</b>: addresses support capacity, not data replication frequency.</span><span class='qd'><b>Extending the vendor support contract</b>: relates to support terms, not backup/replication frequency.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reducing the number of firewall rules</b>: is a network security configuration change unrelated to data-loss tolerance.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-085","domain":4,"obj":"4B3","diff":"hard","q":"An organization has a robust DRP for IT systems but no documented BCP for business operations. During a prolonged data center outage, which gap is MOST likely to emerge?","options":["IT systems will fail to restore at all due to the missing BCP","The DRP will become legally invalid without an accompanying BCP","Business units will lack guidance on manual workarounds and interim processes despite IT eventually restoring systems","No gap will emerge, since DRP alone covers all continuity needs"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Business units will lack guidance on manual workarounds and interim processes despite IT eventually restoring systems</strong> — without a BCP, business units have no defined interim procedures to keep critical functions running while technical recovery proceeds under the DRP, creating an operational gap.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>IT systems will fail to restore at all due to the missing BCP</b>: the DRP still governs technical restoration; a missing BCP does not by itself break the DRP's execution.</span><span class='qd'><b>The DRP will become legally invalid without an accompanying BCP</b>: there is no general rule invalidating a DRP due to a missing separate BCP.</span><span class='qd'><b>No gap will emerge, since DRP alone covers all continuity needs</b>: incorrectly assumes DRP scope covers business process continuity, which it does not.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-086","domain":4,"obj":"4B4","diff":"med","q":"An organization operating in a highly regulated industry with a near-zero RTO requirement for its trading platform is MOST likely to select which recovery strategy?","options":["A cold site activated only after a formal disaster declaration","A fully mirrored hot site with active-active or active-passive real-time failover","A reciprocal agreement with a competitor in the same industry","Reliance on nightly backups restored to newly procured hardware"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A fully mirrored hot site with active-active or active-passive real-time failover</strong> — a near-zero RTO requirement demands continuously synchronized, immediately available infrastructure, which only a hot site configuration can deliver.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A cold site activated only after a formal disaster declaration</b>: would produce a recovery time of days, incompatible with near-zero RTO.</span><span class='qd'><b>A reciprocal agreement with a competitor in the same industry</b>: is impractical due to competitive conflicts and typically cannot meet near-zero RTO.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reliance on nightly backups restored to newly procured hardware</b>: would take far too long to meet a near-zero RTO requirement.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-087","domain":4,"obj":"4A4","diff":"med","q":"Which factor should MOST influence the decision to take a system fully offline (aggressive containment) versus applying more limited network segmentation?","options":["The personal preference of whichever engineer is on call","The color of the alert in the SIEM dashboard","The number of years the system has been in production","The severity of ongoing damage weighed against the business criticality and cost of downtime"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The severity of ongoing damage weighed against the business criticality and cost of downtime</strong> — containment decisions require balancing the urgency of stopping damage against the operational cost of taking a critical system offline, a risk-based judgment call.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The personal preference of whichever engineer is on call</b>: containment decisions should follow documented risk-based criteria, not individual preference.</span><span class='qd'><b>The color of the alert in the SIEM dashboard</b>: is a visual indicator, not a substantive decision factor.</span><span class='qd'><b>The number of years the system has been in production</b>: system age is not directly relevant to containment strategy decisions.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-088","domain":4,"obj":"4A5","diff":"easy","q":"Which activity is generally considered part of eradication?","options":["Removing malware and disabling any accounts or backdoors created by the attacker","Restoring the system to full production status","Informing customers about the resolution","Filing the final incident closure report"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Removing malware and disabling any accounts or backdoors created by the attacker</strong> — eradication focuses on eliminating the threat and any persistence mechanisms left by the attacker.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Restoring the system to full production status</b>: is a recovery activity, occurring after eradication is complete.</span><span class='qd'><b>Informing customers about the resolution</b>: is a communications activity, separate from technical eradication.</span><span class='qd'><b>Filing the final incident closure report</b>: occurs during post-incident activity, well after eradication.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-089","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"med","q":"An incident responder wants to capture the contents of RAM on a live, compromised server before shutting it down. Which forensic principle is being applied?","options":["Chain of custody, since the responder is transferring evidence to another handler","Least privilege, since RAM access must be restricted","Order of volatility, since RAM contents are lost when power is removed","Data classification, since RAM often contains labeled data"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Order of volatility, since RAM contents are lost when power is removed</strong> — capturing volatile memory before it is lost due to shutdown is a direct application of collecting the most volatile evidence first.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Chain of custody, since the responder is transferring evidence to another handler</b>: chain of custody concerns tracking evidence handling, not the decision of what to capture first.</span><span class='qd'><b>Least privilege, since RAM access must be restricted</b>: is an access control concept, unrelated to the volatility-driven capture decision.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data classification, since RAM often contains labeled data</b>: is unrelated to the timing rationale for capturing volatile memory.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-090","domain":4,"obj":"4A7","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following is a common REQUIRED element of a breach notification to affected individuals under many data protection laws?","options":["The internal salary of the employee who caused the breach","A description of the nature of the breach and the categories of data involved","The exact source code of the affected application","The organization's complete network topology diagram"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A description of the nature of the breach and the categories of data involved</strong> — most breach notification laws require informing affected individuals about what happened and what type of personal data was involved, so they can take protective action.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The internal salary of the employee who caused the breach</b>: is irrelevant personal information that has no place in a breach notification.</span><span class='qd'><b>The exact source code of the affected application</b>: is sensitive intellectual property, not something disclosed to affected individuals.</span><span class='qd'><b>The organization's complete network topology diagram</b>: would create additional security risk and is not a required disclosure element.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-091","domain":4,"obj":"4A8","diff":"med","q":"Which metric measures the average time between an incident occurring and the organization becoming aware of it?","options":["Mean time to repair (MTTR)","Recovery time objective (RTO)","Maximum tolerable downtime (MTD)","Mean time to detect (MTTD)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Mean time to detect (MTTD)</strong> — MTTD specifically measures detection latency, the gap between when an incident begins and when it is discovered.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Mean time to repair (MTTR)</b>: measures how long it takes to fix an issue once identified, not detection latency.</span><span class='qd'><b>Recovery time objective (RTO)</b>: is a planning target for restoration time, not an average historical detection measurement.</span><span class='qd'><b>Maximum tolerable downtime (MTD)</b>: represents the outer downtime tolerance limit, unrelated to detection speed.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-092","domain":4,"obj":"4A9","diff":"hard","q":"An organization's post-incident review reveals that the CSIRT followed the documented plan correctly, yet the incident still caused significant damage because the plan itself contained an outdated escalation contact list. What is the MOST appropriate conclusion?","options":["The plan requires a change in maintenance process to ensure contact information stays current, even though execution was sound","The CSIRT members should be disciplined for following an outdated plan","The incident response plan should be abandoned entirely","No changes are needed since the team followed the plan as written"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The plan requires a change in maintenance process to ensure contact information stays current, even though execution was sound</strong> — the root cause here is a plan maintenance gap, not personnel failure; fixing the underlying process for keeping the plan current addresses the true issue.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The CSIRT members should be disciplined for following an outdated plan</b>: unfairly blames the team for correctly executing a plan that was not properly maintained.</span><span class='qd'><b>The incident response plan should be abandoned entirely</b>: is a disproportionate reaction to a single outdated data element within the plan.</span><span class='qd'><b>No changes are needed since the team followed the plan as written</b>: ignores the clear need to fix the plan maintenance process that allowed outdated information to persist.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-093","domain":4,"obj":"4B5","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following would be the MOST appropriate first DR test for an organization that has never conducted one before?","options":["A full interruption test of all critical systems","An unannounced surprise full failover during business hours","A tabletop exercise or structured walkthrough","Skipping testing and going directly to live production cutover"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A tabletop exercise or structured walkthrough</strong> — for an organization new to testing, starting with a lower-risk, discussion-based exercise builds familiarity and surfaces basic gaps before attempting higher-risk, live tests.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A full interruption test of all critical systems</b>: is high-risk and generally reserved for mature programs with proven, lower-risk testing history.</span><span class='qd'><b>An unannounced surprise full failover during business hours</b>: is reckless for an inexperienced organization and could cause unplanned business disruption.</span><span class='qd'><b>Skipping testing and going directly to live production cutover</b>: abandons the entire purpose of controlled testing before a real event.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-094","domain":4,"obj":"4B6","diff":"med","q":"Which statement about the relationship between RTO and cost of recovery solutions is generally TRUE?","options":["Shorter RTOs always cost less because less data needs to be recovered","Shorter RTOs typically require more expensive recovery solutions, such as hot sites","RTO has no bearing on the cost of the chosen recovery strategy","Longer RTOs always require hot sites to remain compliant"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Shorter RTOs typically require more expensive recovery solutions, such as hot sites</strong> — achieving faster recovery generally demands more sophisticated, continuously ready infrastructure, which increases cost.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Shorter RTOs always cost less because less data needs to be recovered</b>: confuses RTO (time to restore) with RPO (data loss), and misstates the typical cost relationship.</span><span class='qd'><b>RTO has no bearing on the cost of the chosen recovery strategy</b>: contradicts the well-established inverse relationship between RTO and cost.</span><span class='qd'><b>Longer RTOs always require hot sites to remain compliant</b>: reverses the relationship; longer RTOs can typically be met with cheaper cold or warm sites.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-095","domain":4,"obj":"4B7","diff":"med","q":"During a declared disaster, who is generally responsible for authorizing external communications to customers and the media?","options":["Any technical staff member who is available at the time","The recovery site's facilities vendor","The forensic investigator handling the case","A designated public relations or communications lead working under crisis management authority"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A designated public relations or communications lead working under crisis management authority</strong> — external messaging should be controlled by a designated communications role operating within the crisis management structure to ensure accuracy and consistency.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Any technical staff member who is available at the time</b>: risks inconsistent or technically inaccurate public statements without proper authorization.</span><span class='qd'><b>The recovery site's facilities vendor</b>: has no authority or responsibility over the organization's public communications.</span><span class='qd'><b>The forensic investigator handling the case</b>: focuses on evidence collection and analysis, not public messaging.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-096","domain":4,"obj":"4B8","diff":"hard","q":"An internal audit finds that the DR plan was last tested three years ago and several key systems have since been migrated to cloud infrastructure. What is the MOST significant risk this finding highlights?","options":["The plan may no longer accurately reflect the current environment, making recovery assumptions unreliable during a real event","The audit itself is invalid since DR plans do not require testing","Cloud migration automatically eliminates the need for DR planning","The finding is immaterial since the plan was tested at some point"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The plan may no longer accurately reflect the current environment, making recovery assumptions unreliable during a real event</strong> — significant infrastructure changes since the last test mean the plan's assumptions about systems, dependencies, and procedures are likely stale and unreliable.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The audit itself is invalid since DR plans do not require testing</b>: DR plans absolutely require regular testing; this option misstates a basic principle.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cloud migration automatically eliminates the need for DR planning</b>: cloud infrastructure still requires DR planning tailored to the new environment, not elimination of planning.</span><span class='qd'><b>The finding is immaterial since the plan was tested at some point</b>: understates the real risk created by three years of drift and major infrastructure change.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-097","domain":4,"obj":"4A2","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the purpose of the 'Post-Incident Activity' phase in the incident response lifecycle?","options":["Detecting anomalous activity for the first time","Isolating compromised systems from the network","Reviewing the incident to capture lessons learned and improve future response","Declaring a state of emergency to executive leadership"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Reviewing the incident to capture lessons learned and improve future response</strong> — this final lifecycle phase closes the loop by analyzing the response and driving improvements to plans, tools, and training.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Detecting anomalous activity for the first time</b>: describes the detection and analysis phase, which occurs much earlier.</span><span class='qd'><b>Isolating compromised systems from the network</b>: is a containment activity, not a post-incident review activity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Declaring a state of emergency to executive leadership</b>: typically occurs during escalation, well before post-incident review.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-098","domain":4,"obj":"4A3","diff":"med","q":"An organization's incident classification policy defines 'Severity 1' as incidents causing complete outage of revenue-generating systems. A partial outage affecting a non-critical internal reporting tool should generally be classified as:","options":["Severity 1, because any outage must be treated identically","A lower severity level, reflecting its limited business impact","Not an incident at all, since it is only internal","A disaster requiring full BCP activation"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A lower severity level, reflecting its limited business impact</strong> — because severity classification is driven by actual business impact, a partial outage of a non-critical internal tool warrants a lower classification than a complete outage of revenue-generating systems.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Severity 1, because any outage must be treated identically</b>: contradicts the entire purpose of impact-based severity classification.</span><span class='qd'><b>Not an incident at all, since it is only internal</b>: an internal-only impact can still qualify as a legitimate, lower-severity incident.</span><span class='qd'><b>A disaster requiring full BCP activation</b>: vastly overstates the scale of a minor, non-critical outage.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-099","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following is typically the FIRST step in conducting a business impact analysis?","options":["Selecting a recovery site vendor","Writing the final disaster recovery runbook","Purchasing cyber insurance coverage","Identifying critical business processes and their supporting resources"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Identifying critical business processes and their supporting resources</strong> — the BIA begins by cataloging business processes and their dependencies before impact and recovery requirements can be assessed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Selecting a recovery site vendor</b>: is a downstream decision made after BIA and risk analysis findings are known.</span><span class='qd'><b>Writing the final disaster recovery runbook</b>: is a later deliverable built upon BIA findings, not the first step.</span><span class='qd'><b>Purchasing cyber insurance coverage</b>: is a risk transfer decision that typically follows, not precedes, impact analysis.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-100","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"hard","q":"An organization must choose between two backup strategies for a critical application: Strategy A replicates data continuously with near-zero RPO but costs significantly more, while Strategy B backs up every 6 hours at a much lower cost. The BIA shows the application supports a payment system where even minutes of lost transactions cause material financial and regulatory harm. Which strategy is MOST appropriate?","options":["Strategy A, because the BIA indicates an extremely low data-loss tolerance that only near-zero RPO replication can satisfy","Strategy B, because lower cost should always take priority over recovery objectives","Strategy A, but only for non-critical reporting systems, not payment systems","Strategy B, since backup frequency has no relationship to RPO"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Strategy A, because the BIA indicates an extremely low data-loss tolerance that only near-zero RPO replication can satisfy</strong> — since the BIA reveals that even minutes of data loss cause material harm, the organization's actual RPO requirement is near zero, which only continuous replication can meet, justifying the higher cost.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Strategy B, because lower cost should always take priority over recovery objectives</b>: ignores the BIA finding that data loss tolerance is extremely low, making cost a secondary concern here.</span><span class='qd'><b>Strategy A, but only for non-critical reporting systems, not payment systems</b>: reverses the logic; the payment system is precisely the critical system that needs the stronger protection.</span><span class='qd'><b>Strategy B, since backup frequency has no relationship to RPO</b>: is factually incorrect; backup/replication frequency directly determines achievable RPO.</span>"}
]);
